00:19:03,400 --> 00:19:04,400
That's impressive, man.

330
00:19:04,440 --> 00:19:05,020
That's cool.

331
00:19:06,940 --> 00:19:10,240
Well, while working at Los Alamos National Lab in 1982,

332
00:19:10,240 --> 00:19:14,160
the local newspaper did a front-page story on a jet car I had built.

333
00:19:15,040 --> 00:19:19,060
Coincidentally, Dr. Edward Teller was giving a speech at Los Alamos that same day.

334
00:19:22,500 --> 00:19:26,740
So Edward Teller, for the audience, was the creator of the hydrogen bomb.

335
00:19:27,780 --> 00:19:32,320
Coincidentally, that same day on the paper, if you turn over the front sheet,

336
00:19:32,620 --> 00:19:36,280
was the advertisement for Ed Teller coming the next day.

337
00:19:36,440 --> 00:19:36,840
Wow.

338
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:38,980
Giving a lecture, you know, at the lab, so.

339
00:19:40,240 --> 00:19:45,460
So you go to, like, a talk he gives or something?

340
00:19:45,580 --> 00:19:47,000
Yeah, he was about to give a talk.

341
00:19:47,060 --> 00:19:47,820
I got there early.

342
00:19:48,020 --> 00:19:51,540
He's sitting outside reading the paper because the door was locked.

343
00:19:51,720 --> 00:19:51,940
Uh-huh.

344
00:19:51,940 --> 00:19:57,440
So that's, I wanted to go super early, too, because I thought maybe it's going to be crowded or whatever.

345
00:19:59,160 --> 00:20:05,560
He's reading the front page of the paper because, or else I really didn't know how to go out and say anything,

346
00:20:05,560 --> 00:20:07,540
but I went, oh, it's the perfect segue.

347
00:20:07,760 --> 00:20:09,660
He's already reading about me.

348
00:20:09,720 --> 00:20:12,720
So I was like, hi, Ed, I'm the guy you're reading about there.

349
00:20:12,720 --> 00:20:14,480
What was Edward Teller like?

350
00:20:14,860 --> 00:20:16,120
He's a grumpy old man.

351
00:20:17,380 --> 00:20:19,740
That's just the only way I could describe him.

352
00:20:19,940 --> 00:20:23,840
Did he have any sort of distinct accent or facial?

353
00:20:23,840 --> 00:20:24,700
Of course he has a distinct accent.

354
00:20:26,220 --> 00:20:27,480
Ed Teller, yeah.

355
00:20:27,580 --> 00:20:27,840
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

356
00:20:27,840 --> 00:20:28,700
A bit thick Hungarian.

357
00:20:28,700 --> 00:20:30,540
Yeah, he had giant eyebrows and, yeah.

358
00:20:30,720 --> 00:20:30,900
Yeah.

359
00:20:31,060 --> 00:20:33,120
I mean, he looked exactly like himself.

360
00:20:33,340 --> 00:20:34,040
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

361
00:20:34,700 --> 00:20:35,140
Fascinating.

362
00:20:35,300 --> 00:20:37,000
And so what was the conversation like?

363
00:20:37,040 --> 00:20:38,800
Are you like, hey, that, you know, that's me.

364
00:20:38,900 --> 00:20:40,360
And then what did he, what did he say?

365
00:20:40,860 --> 00:20:42,800
He said, well, that's, that's fascinating.

366
00:20:42,800 --> 00:20:46,140
But, you know, I can't remember it verbatim, but he said.

367
00:20:46,300 --> 00:20:48,080
But it is grossly impractical.

368
00:20:49,200 --> 00:20:54,620
I said, yeah, it's not made to be a practical, you know, mode of transportation.

369
00:20:55,120 --> 00:21:00,200
And then we only spoke for a short time and then you can hear the door unclick, swing open.

370
00:21:00,300 --> 00:21:02,160
And a guy greeted him, oh, Mr. Teller.

371
00:21:02,160 --> 00:21:05,760
And so they brought him in and, you know, that was that.

372
00:21:05,940 --> 00:21:13,980
But as time went on, I made reference to that meeting when I sent him a resume after I had moved on from Los Alamos.

373
00:21:14,320 --> 00:21:16,360
And he remembered me.

374
00:21:16,940 --> 00:21:22,780
And that's who directed me to EG&G, how this all started to go to S4.

375
00:21:22,780 --> 00:21:32,260
Have you ever seen, there's a, there's a video of, um, Edward Teller being questioned on his relationship with you?

376
00:21:32,500 --> 00:21:32,880
Yeah, yeah, of course.

377
00:21:32,880 --> 00:21:40,700
It's really funny because he, first of all, he goes into, he's being questioned on nuclear propulsion and he, like, doesn't want to get into it.

378
00:21:40,720 --> 00:21:41,420
It's very clear.

379
00:21:41,680 --> 00:21:44,520
And then he's questioning on you and he has the exact same reaction.

380
00:21:44,520 --> 00:21:47,840
It is, in my opinion, not interesting.

381
00:21:48,660 --> 00:21:50,520
I don't intend to answer it.

382
00:21:50,760 --> 00:21:53,960
If you ask me that question on camera, I will shut up.

383
00:21:54,200 --> 00:21:55,020
I will sit silent.

384
00:21:56,500 --> 00:21:58,840
You're not going to get an answer right on me on that.

385
00:21:59,900 --> 00:22:00,340
Okay.

386
00:22:02,260 --> 00:22:05,340
And if I ask you on camera if you know Bob Lazar, can you just say no?

387
00:22:06,920 --> 00:22:08,480
I will sit silently.

388
00:22:08,480 --> 00:22:16,760
I mean, I spoke to the guy before he went and interviewed Teller.

389
00:22:17,060 --> 00:22:18,760
He was one of Teller's students.

390
00:22:19,360 --> 00:22:23,320
And he said, you know, I'm going to bring up you to Teller.

391
00:22:23,420 --> 00:22:24,660
And I went, that would be awesome.

392
00:22:24,940 --> 00:22:25,140
Yeah.

393
00:22:25,280 --> 00:22:29,460
And it would be awesome to see how fast he denies me.

394
00:22:29,640 --> 00:22:29,860
Yeah.

395
00:22:30,020 --> 00:22:31,920
You know, and he did immediately.

396
00:22:32,280 --> 00:22:34,080
But he denied you in the same way.

397
00:22:34,080 --> 00:22:39,240
First, he goes, yeah, technically you could get, you know, a real power source from nuclear.

398
00:22:39,900 --> 00:22:43,420
And basically implying he knows a lot about it, but he's not going to talk about it.

399
00:22:43,480 --> 00:22:43,600
Yeah.

400
00:22:43,700 --> 00:22:47,240
I think he said, yeah, is there anything other than fish and refusion?

401
00:22:47,460 --> 00:22:47,880
That's right.

402
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:50,320
No, nothing that anybody interested about.

403
00:22:50,460 --> 00:22:50,580
Yeah.

404
00:22:50,640 --> 00:22:53,200
But there's total annihilation, you know.

405
00:22:53,520 --> 00:22:59,000
And yeah, he just completely discounted that, which is interesting for Teller.

406
00:22:59,120 --> 00:23:04,060
Do you think that he is talking about, because you talk about this 115, you had a problem.

407
00:23:04,080 --> 00:23:05,560
I don't know if that's what he was referring to.

408
00:23:05,560 --> 00:23:08,760
Goes up to 116, and then you get this matter, antimatter annihilation thing.

409
00:23:08,760 --> 00:23:14,300
I don't know if that's what he was referring to, but he's also, but he's clearly not addressing

410
00:23:14,300 --> 00:23:17,000
the most powerful nuclear reaction there is.

411
00:23:17,060 --> 00:23:18,340
And why would he do that?

412
00:23:18,340 --> 00:23:24,300
And he's clearly also denying the nuclear knowledge in the same way that he's denying

413
00:23:24,300 --> 00:23:25,840
his link to you.

414
00:23:26,260 --> 00:23:29,060
Which to me is such a tell that he obviously met you.

415
00:23:29,700 --> 00:23:29,900
Yeah.

416
00:23:31,420 --> 00:23:33,340
It's really weird that he would do that.

417
00:23:33,340 --> 00:23:39,720
And so you were at Los Alamos, and were you working with other physicists at the time?

418
00:23:39,820 --> 00:23:39,900
Yeah, yeah.

419
00:23:39,900 --> 00:23:43,960
Or what was your main kind of like day-to-day responsibility there?

420
00:23:44,600 --> 00:23:46,440
Well, it changed.

421
00:23:46,440 --> 00:23:53,320
Um, I did some, I was building, I think, uh, this was for the particle accelerator.

422
00:23:53,500 --> 00:23:58,760
They wanted to be able to trim the voltage to a very fine degree.

423
00:23:59,040 --> 00:24:05,900
So I was building some high voltage power supplies, stuff that's insulated by fiber optics, so you

424
00:24:05,900 --> 00:24:12,940
can make adjustments, you know, from a distance without interfering with, you know, the electric

425
00:24:12,940 --> 00:24:13,940
fields or anything.

426
00:24:14,600 --> 00:24:20,120
Um, and day-to-day there was just maintenance on the targets and experiments we were doing.

427
00:24:20,320 --> 00:24:26,340
So it's cryogenics and, you know, dealing with, uh, high power magnets.

428
00:24:26,340 --> 00:24:29,060
And, I mean, what else?

429
00:24:29,180 --> 00:24:30,320
Radio actors' materials.

430
00:24:31,020 --> 00:24:31,080
Yeah.

431
00:24:31,520 --> 00:24:34,760
Um, you know, Los Alamos stuff.

432
00:24:34,900 --> 00:24:35,100
Yeah.

433
00:24:35,120 --> 00:24:39,320
I mean, I'm just trying to remember what I did every day, but it was, uh, nothing, it

434
00:24:39,320 --> 00:24:42,560
was, there was no really regular routine.

435
00:24:42,820 --> 00:24:43,080
Mm-hmm.

436
00:24:43,080 --> 00:24:48,920
You know, we'd either be working on getting ready to do an experiment, so we'd be working

437
00:24:48,920 --> 00:24:50,800
on, you know, the detection equipment.

438
00:24:51,000 --> 00:24:51,180
Yeah.

439
00:24:51,340 --> 00:24:52,880
Or setting up the experiment.

440
00:24:53,560 --> 00:25:03,260
And, um, it all had to do with, uh, you know, the output of the accelerator and adjusting

441
00:25:03,260 --> 00:25:03,620
that.

442
00:25:04,060 --> 00:25:05,840
So this was a particle accelerator?

443
00:25:06,100 --> 00:25:06,480
Yeah, yeah.

444
00:25:06,660 --> 00:25:07,340
Oh, interesting.

445
00:25:07,680 --> 00:25:11,200
Yeah, it's a half mile long linear accelerator in Los Alamos.

446
00:25:11,320 --> 00:25:11,720
Oh, cool.

447
00:25:11,720 --> 00:25:20,220
And the beam splits off, it, uh, it comes down and it, it splits off into different experimental

448
00:25:20,220 --> 00:25:20,800
areas.

449
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:26,680
So you can conduct a whole bunch of different experiments, you know, just from one, one beam.

450
00:25:26,820 --> 00:25:30,420
And they can put different things in the targets to make different particles and go different

451
00:25:30,420 --> 00:25:30,920
directions.

452
00:25:30,920 --> 00:25:37,500
And depending on the speed of the particle going by and its spin and how long it's in transit,

453
00:25:37,500 --> 00:25:42,280
you can calculate its mass and, you know, backtrack and then put things together.

454
00:25:42,700 --> 00:25:48,740
And, you know, analogy I always gave was, uh, it's, it's like if you wanted to analyze

455
00:25:48,740 --> 00:25:52,280
a Swiss watch, but you really couldn't look inside.

456
00:25:52,280 --> 00:25:59,960
But so you could take it and throw it as hard as you can at a concrete wall and then it busts

457
00:25:59,960 --> 00:26:02,160
apart and all the pieces go flying off.

458
00:26:02,360 --> 00:26:02,520
Yeah.

459
00:26:03,040 --> 00:26:06,380
Well, by looking at those pieces, you could backtrack everything.

460
00:26:06,920 --> 00:26:06,980
Yeah.

461
00:26:07,020 --> 00:26:12,160
You could see if one was spinning a certain direction and you know, the rotation and how

462
00:26:12,160 --> 00:26:17,200
fast it came off, then, you know, the mass of it, if it was turning before and by the

463
00:26:17,200 --> 00:26:22,120
angles, you can put it back there and eventually you can reassemble the thing and see how it

464
00:26:22,120 --> 00:26:24,220
was made just from the particles flying apart.

465
00:26:24,400 --> 00:26:29,080
So essentially what an accelerator does is smash something apart and then we can figure

466
00:26:29,080 --> 00:26:32,760
out how it all goes together just by monitoring those particles.

467
00:26:33,020 --> 00:26:33,700
It's so cool.

468
00:26:34,360 --> 00:26:34,800
Yeah.

469
00:26:34,920 --> 00:26:37,820
So, I mean, that's, that's, that's what I did at Los Alamos.

470
00:26:37,820 --> 00:26:44,780
Did you, did you get the sense that there were two branches of science, science that

471
00:26:44,780 --> 00:26:47,880
was a little more classified and then public science?

472
00:26:48,100 --> 00:26:48,820
No, not at that point.

473
00:26:48,820 --> 00:26:49,540
Not at that point.

474
00:26:49,560 --> 00:26:50,120
Not at that point.

475
00:26:50,240 --> 00:26:51,780
I thought we were all on the same level.

476
00:26:52,080 --> 00:26:52,340
Yeah.

477
00:26:53,100 --> 00:27:00,840
Now I know, um, you can't say why they erased you from MIT and there are a lot of people out

478
00:27:00,840 --> 00:27:03,120
there who say you faked your educational credentials.

479
00:27:03,120 --> 00:27:09,040
You have very good, I think, reason that at least passes, you know, Joe Rogan and some

480
00:27:09,040 --> 00:27:11,480
other people who I really trust their sniff test.

481
00:27:12,160 --> 00:27:17,760
He said that he was working on something for the government at, and they sent him to MIT

482
